35:31.840 --> 35:33.120
      He's got to know that.

35:33.120 --> 35:37.000
If you don't respond now,
some day he'll push all
of your buttons

35:37.000 --> 35:41.000
and you'll lose control.
That's not what punishment's about.

35:46.240 --> 35:47.880
KNOCK ON DOOR

35:47.880 --> 35:50.360
Elliott?
Open up. &gt;

35:50.360 --> 35:51.440
             Coming...

35:51.440 --> 35:54.360
What's so important that you
couldn't tell me over the phone? &gt;

35:54.360 --> 35:55.920
       I'll be right there.

35:55.920 --> 35:59.120
Hurry up, Elliott. &gt;

35:59.120 --> 36:00.600
        Want a pina colada?

36:00.600 --> 36:02.920
No, and I don't have much time!

36:02.920 --> 36:06.080
I'm supposed to be
taking a patient down to radiology.

36:06.080 --> 36:09.200
It's about Julius.
He was pacing around in his cage like

36:09.200 --> 36:11.560
   he had no chance for parole,

36:11.560 --> 36:14.720
so I opened up the cage to let him
like stretch his wings a bit.

36:14.720 --> 36:16.160
Well, where is he?

36:16.160 --> 36:20.160
Last time I saw him
he was in here, but he's gone.

36:20.440 --> 36:22.960
   Luther, he's flown the coop.

36:22.960 --> 36:24.080
Julius?

36:24.080 --> 36:26.360
He was sailing around
my apartment before

36:26.360 --> 36:28.320
  I realised the window was open.

36:28.320 --> 36:31.080
Hey, don't worry.

36:31.080 --> 36:32.800
          But he's gone.

36:32.800 --> 36:36.360
Elliott, he's a homing pigeon.
He'll be back.

36:36.360 --> 36:40.160
But it's cold outside.
I mean, his wings iced up.

36:40.160 --> 36:42.960
      Snow clogged his radar.

36:42.960 --> 36:44.480
Julius...

36:44.480 --> 36:48.480
           What's wrong?

36:52.600 --> 36:55.360
He must have landed there,

36:55.360 --> 36:57.680
and froze to death,

36:57.680 --> 37:01.080
warming down from his flight.

37:01.080 --> 37:05.080
He was always flying
       that extra mile,

37:05.240 --> 37:09.240
pushing himself to the limit.

37:11.320 --> 37:15.320
That's why he soared like an eagle.

37:16.760 --> 37:18.280
Wait, I want to get out!

37:18.280 --> 37:19.920
Where the hell have you been?

37:19.920 --> 37:21.360
Back there the whole time.

37:21.360 --> 37:23.400
You would have known that if you
checked your mirror.

37:23.400 --> 37:26.080
You would have known that if you
checked your mirror.
That was stupid running
     away like that.

37:26.080 --> 37:28.600
You're not exactly
the smartest person I know.

37:28.600 --> 37:31.080
This has got to stop,
      the disobedience!

37:31.080 --> 37:32.400
The talking back to me!

37:32.400 --> 37:35.200
Do you understand? You're going
 to start listening, damn it!

37:35.200 --> 37:37.960
You're crazy!
First you hit that nurse at work...

37:37.960 --> 37:39.240
You needed this!

37:39.240 --> 37:41.760
Then why can't you be
normal like other kids' moms?!

37:41.760 --> 37:44.760
I'm sorry if you don't like the way
things are run around here,

37:44.760 --> 37:46.000
but I'm still
     the head of this house.

37:46.000 --> 37:50.000
but I'm still
     the head of this house.
I want to live with my dad.

37:59.160 --> 38:02.640
Mona!
I was just on my way up to see you.

38:02.640 --> 38:03.880
         We need to talk.

38:03.880 --> 38:04.920
Yeah...

38:04.920 --> 38:08.920
Look, that night during the blackout,
I was so scared.

38:09.480 --> 38:12.120
    And you were so reassuring.

38:12.120 --> 38:16.120
The time we spent in a storage
room was really special. Romantic.

38:16.160 --> 38:19.000
Look, if you don't want to
get married, you just say so.

38:19.000 --> 38:20.440
  You don't want to get married.

38:20.440 --> 38:21.520
No, that's not true.

38:21.520 --> 38:23.000
Then why are you on
your way up to see me?

38:23.000 --> 38:26.680
Then why are you on
your way up to see me?
Because...do I need a
reason to talk to my fiancee?

38:26.680 --> 38:29.000
    Ex. I knew you'd back out.

38:29.000 --> 38:31.000
Then why'd you tell your parents?

38:31.000 --> 38:32.920
 I never even picked up the phone.

38:32.920 --> 38:35.400
Because you had no
intention of marrying me.

38:35.400 --> 38:38.120
All you think about is being
Craig's stooge in the OR.

38:38.120 --> 38:39.680
And if we did get married,
you'd have no time for me.

38:39.680 --> 38:43.680
And if we did get married,
you'd have no time for me.
What about you?! The hot shot doctor
who spends every minute in the ER.

38:43.760 --> 38:46.760
Marriage is 100%, all or
nothing, lifetime commitment.

38:46.760 --> 38:47.960
Don't you think I know that?  No!

38:47.960 --> 38:50.920
The next time you ask someone to be
your wife, make sure you mean it!

38:50.920 --> 38:54.920
Mona... I hate this... Mona, wait!

38:56.760 --> 39:00.440
Luther,
I'm carrying around a lot of guilt.

39:00.440 --> 39:02.880
So bounce into McCabe chapel.

39:02.880 --> 39:05.160
 No, I have to tell you something.

39:05.160 --> 39:08.560
Not now, Elliott, OK, I just
lost my best friend today.

39:08.560 --> 39:11.440
I killed Julius. It was an accident.
I was making him a bird bath

39:11.440 --> 39:13.920
and the radio fell in
and he got electrocuted.

39:13.920 --> 39:15.720
But he was on the window ledge.

39:15.720 --> 39:19.720
I tried to make you think
that he'd frozen to death.

39:21.360 --> 39:23.280
Do you think he felt any pain?

39:23.280 --> 39:25.120
Uh-uh, It was 30 amps, straight up.

39:25.120 --> 39:28.400
I even had to replace
the blown fuse afterwards.

39:28.400 --> 39:32.400
Maybe it was all for the best.

39:34.440 --> 39:37.200
You're right, Julius was decrepit.

39:37.200 --> 39:38.760
He was valiant.

39:38.760 --> 39:42.240
Luther, he was 210 years old
in people years.

39:42.240 --> 39:44.360
    Ask my father, he's a vet.

39:44.360 --> 39:47.240
I found Julius on the mall,
in the arms of Paul Revere.

39:47.240 --> 39:51.200
You know the statue.
It was raining and he was sick.

39:51.200 --> 39:53.760
And I took him home and fed him
 with an eye dropper.

39:53.760 --> 39:55.440
Let him live in my closet.

39:55.440 --> 39:58.520
Luther, face it,
his racing days were over.

39:58.520 --> 40:00.400
I nursed Julius back to health

40:00.400 --> 40:04.400
and then in return he gave me
loyalty and companionship.

40:09.240 --> 40:13.240
You know, Luther,
Julius had one, maybe two years left.

40:14.280 --> 40:16.600
Pigeons know when it's their time.

40:16.600 --> 40:19.680
They stop eating or they
find the wall and fly into it.

40:19.680 --> 40:23.680
But you know, Julius dying in
a flash, I mean, a shower of sparks.

40:23.800 --> 40:27.800
Besides, now you can concentrate
on your paramedic training.

40:27.960 --> 40:30.840
You can forget about all this
pigeon racing stuff.

40:30.840 --> 40:33.760
Julius flew his heart out for me.

40:33.760 --> 40:37.360
And I loved him.

40:37.360 --> 40:41.360
 Luther, he was just a dumb bird.

40:44.080 --> 40:46.600
I trusted you! I trusted you
   to take care of Julius,

40:46.600 --> 40:49.320
not play the executioner's song!

40:49.320 --> 40:53.320
I won't forget you for this,
   Axelrod!

40:54.200 --> 40:55.680
Elliott, are you all right?

40:55.680 --> 40:59.680
       Yeah. I'm all right.

41:03.040 --> 41:04.160
              Thanks.

41:04.160 --> 41:08.160
Here.

42:15.440 --> 42:19.200
Yeah. &gt;

42:19.200 --> 42:20.760
Hey, Jack, what can I do for you?

42:20.760 --> 42:22.440
       You're busy, I'll...

42:22.440 --> 42:23.760
Come in.
If I talk to you,

42:23.760 --> 42:27.760
I won't think about what I'm eating.

42:32.840 --> 42:33.920
How's little Pete?

42:33.920 --> 42:36.640
He's fine, he's got
another birthday coming up.

42:36.640 --> 42:39.360
Must be getting to be
quite a handful, isn't he?

42:39.360 --> 42:41.080
           How's Tommy?

42:41.080 --> 42:43.960
He's all right.
I had to bring him to the hospital,

42:43.960 --> 42:45.560
he's asleep in on call.

42:45.560 --> 42:48.880
          Where's Marina?

42:48.880 --> 42:52.880
She's gone.

42:53.520 --> 42:56.520
You ever think about
going back to Ethiopia?

42:56.520 --> 42:59.480
I'll tell you something,
if I didn't have those pictures

42:59.480 --> 43:01.280
to remind me,

43:01.280 --> 43:03.640
it would seem like
I'd never been there.

43:03.640 --> 43:07.320
You know, I thought I'd changed
 when I went over there.

43:07.320 --> 43:10.480
I thought the experience
   of that had made me stronger

43:10.480 --> 43:13.040
and wiser, more committed.

43:13.040 --> 43:16.280
I really thought that I could
 pull that sword out of the stone

43:16.280 --> 43:18.360
and fix what was broken
     in the world.

43:18.360 --> 43:19.920
You fight
for what you believe in.

43:19.920 --> 43:22.440
I was asked to do something
today that I thought

43:22.440 --> 43:26.440
was morally wrong
and instead of standing up,

43:26.520 --> 43:30.520
          I surrendered.

43:30.880 --> 43:33.000
I'm the same guy
       I was before I left.

43:33.000 --> 43:37.000
When I was a kid, I played
    out by Flannery's pub.

43:39.040 --> 43:42.600
Pretty good fielder, couldn't hit.

43:42.600 --> 43:46.600
And every time I'd strike out,
I'd cry.

43:46.800 --> 43:50.800
Well, I'm still a bad loser.

43:51.240 --> 43:54.760
Sometimes it just doesn't
matter what we do, Jack.

43:54.760 --> 43:57.840
One man should be able
to make a difference.

43:57.840 --> 44:01.840
Well, not tonight.

44:02.960 --> 44:05.120
But I guess as long
       as we're breathing,

44:05.120 --> 44:07.440
we get another chance at bat, right?

44:07.440 --> 44:08.400
You hungry?

44:08.400 --> 44:12.400
You hungry?
      Well, actually... Yeah.

44:14.800 --> 44:18.800
Here you go.

